<paragraph blockId="14.[138,1185,1245,1333]" pageId="14" pageNumber="277">
<emphasis box="[138,252,1245,1269]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="277">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Paramere and aedeagus much sclerotized, basally fused to each other, apically pointed (
<figureCitation box="[344,511,1277,1301]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="15.[169,229,797,816]" captionTargetBox="[170,1128,133,761]" captionTargetId="figure-206@15.[170,1128,133,761]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figure 5. Amiota (Amiota) curvispina Chen and Gao, sp. nov. „ (see Figure 4 for further explanation)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4657907" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4657907/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="277">Figure 5D, E</figureCitation>
); paramere lacking sensillum (
<figureCitation box="[875,1041,1277,1301]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="15.[169,229,797,816]" captionTargetBox="[170,1128,133,761]" captionTargetId="figure-206@15.[170,1128,133,761]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figure 5. Amiota (Amiota) curvispina Chen and Gao, sp. nov. „ (see Figure 4 for further explanation)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4657907" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4657907/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="277">Figure 5D, E</figureCitation>
); M-shaped processes of gonopod long, apically much sclerotized and sharply pointed (
<figureCitation box="[1016,1142,1309,1333]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="15.[169,229,797,816]" captionTargetBox="[170,1128,133,761]" captionTargetId="figure-206@15.[170,1128,133,761]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figure 5. Amiota (Amiota) curvispina Chen and Gao, sp. nov. „ (see Figure 4 for further explanation)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4657907" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4657907/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="277">Figure 5C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[138,259,1389,1413]" box="[138,259,1389,1413]" pageId="14" pageNumber="277">
<emphasis box="[138,259,1389,1413]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="277">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[138,1185,1437,1496]" pageId="14" pageNumber="277">
<emphasis box="[138,206,1437,1461]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="277">Wing.</emphasis>
Wing with 
<emphasis box="[358,382,1438,1461]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="277">ca</emphasis>
18–21 minute, peg-like spinules on ventral surface of costal vein between R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[262,295,1479,1496]" fontSize="7" pageId="14" pageNumber="277">2+3</subScript>
and R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[375,408,1479,1496]" fontSize="7" pageId="14" pageNumber="277">4+5</subScript>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[138,1185,1533,1685]" pageId="14" pageNumber="277">
<emphasis box="[138,322,1533,1557]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="277">Male terminalia.</emphasis>
Epandrium constricted heavily, with 
<emphasis box="[765,789,1534,1557]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="277">ca</emphasis>
12 setae from posterior to ventral margins (
<figureCitation box="[250,379,1565,1589]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="15.[169,229,797,816]" captionTargetBox="[170,1128,133,761]" captionTargetId="figure-206@15.[170,1128,133,761]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figure 5. Amiota (Amiota) curvispina Chen and Gao, sp. nov. „ (see Figure 4 for further explanation)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4657907" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4657907/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="277">Figure 5A</figureCitation>
). Surstylus pubescent medially, with three aristate processes fused to each other and forming palm-like lobe on mesal surface, finger-like process at postero-ventral corner, 
<emphasis box="[417,441,1630,1653]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="277">ca</emphasis>
14–15 long prensisetae on distal margin, and a few spine-like stout setae on inner surface (
<figureCitation box="[521,654,1661,1685]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="15.[169,229,797,816]" captionTargetBox="[170,1128,133,761]" captionTargetId="figure-206@15.[170,1128,133,761]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figure 5. Amiota (Amiota) curvispina Chen and Gao, sp. nov. „ (see Figure 4 for further explanation)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4657907" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4657907/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="277">Figure 5B</figureCitation>
). Anterior portion of hypandrium slightly
</paragraph>
