<paragraph blockId="15.[125,1172,1342,1431]" pageId="15" pageNumber="278">
<emphasis box="[125,268,1342,1366]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="278">Relationship.</emphasis>
This species closely resembles 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Okada" authorityYear="1971" box="[678,888,1342,1366]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Amiota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flagellata" subGenus="Amiota">
<emphasis box="[678,705,1342,1366]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="278">A.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[734,761,1342,1366]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="278">A.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[790,888,1342,1366]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="278">flagellata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having the muchsclerotized paramere and aedeagus, but can be distinguished from the latter by the hind tarsus lacking long setae (with long, fringe-like setae in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Okada" authorityYear="1971" box="[777,875,1407,1431]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Amiota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="278" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flagellata">
<emphasis box="[777,875,1407,1431]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="278">flagellata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[125,655,1472,1496]" box="[125,655,1472,1496]" pageId="15" pageNumber="278">
<emphasis box="[125,248,1472,1496]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="278">Etymology.</emphasis>
